Orc Insurgent x2<br />
Isengard Shaman x2<br />
Isengard Warrior x2<br />
Goblin Runner x4<br />
No, that Gimli is not a decklist error. The Origins version was running Gloin. You should have seen the face of the guy who let me go first and saw Gloin and Forest Guardian as my starting fellowship. Lets just say that this fellowship rang the scrub bell by itself.  Not only are dwarves very weak (they die instantly to Nazguls and have strenghts of 6 and 5 with no special ability) but the deck even exerts them so that they die faster. Hobbits are not exactly big fighters either with their streght 3 so the big fighter of the deck was gandalf at 7. I tried to put more muscle in the fellowship for worlds, but a veteran player like Mike saw that the only purpose of the fellowship was to set up the shadow. With the loss of Nertea and so few people playing efficient condition removal, The Underdeeps of Moria becomes a very potent way of killing people at site 7. Initially, the goal of the deck is to set up all your conditions to allow for a 12 to 14 minions swarm at the cavern entrance and should be beaten by any mass condition removal, but the starngest thing happened on day 3 of worlds: I went 4-0 against people running Gandalfand Grown Suddenly Tall, overhwelming them at site 5 and 6 but got beaten by the deck which was not running gandalf because of my fellowship’s weakness. What can I say, this is the most risky deck I have ever played, but also the one that is the most fun to play. And besides, How could I not play dwarves at worlds?<br />
<br />
