<br />
At last, a viable Nazgul shadow. In fact, 5 of my 6 wins on day 2 were shadow kills. Those Nazguls can stop, kill or slow and the sites allow them to do maximum damage. The surprise element is crucial and as such the deck is pretty much history but it did its job. Every player from Montreal were playing this shadow that I designed while drinking wine with my grand parents and the irony of the tiltle was better revealed when me, Dom and Mike Lane were 5-2 before the last game of day 1 and Mike and Dom were paired against each other. The top 8 system dictated that only one of us 3 could make it to day 3 despite all being 5-2 and a little help and fairness from above made me advance. The fellowship is classic Dauntless Hunter heavily inspired by Pat Sullivan’s Origins deck and was allowed to work at its best because of the heavily cycling shadow which killed most anti-Nazgul decks.<br />
<br />
<br />
And thus ends one year of very different decks. From the shadow based ugliest fellowship ever to Dom’s balanced Trust Me and to the Fellowship based Broch Beef, I have tried many different decks to try to bring some money back home. I must admit that meta guessing is a tough discipline indeed and that I have been wrong one more than one occasion, but over this year I have found that constantly striving for new deck ideas is what gives me a chance to succeed.<br />
<br />
I would like to take this opportunity to thank those without whom this bank of decks would be empty:<br />
<br />
My brother, always the one at the core of a new deck idea, whose vision allows us to see good in crappy cards.<br />
Dom Gaudreault, my relentless fellow play-tester, by far a more focused and accurate player than I am.<br />
Pat Sullivan, who by continuing to surprise, obliges us to learn from him.<br />
<br />
And more widely:<br />
<br />
Jonathan Marchi, for designing the deck that inspired us to build the Bad Beef (although we did not include any relentless).<br />
Yannick Lapôinte, for putting the word Tech in “That’s tech”.<br />
Igor from Bulgary for showing me the streght of The Underdeeps of Moria<br />
Gabor Vida for being a visionnary and by himself changing the face of the game.<br />
Marcin Solonczak for designing the most played Lotr deck to this day.<br />
Mike Dalton’s for being responsible for the actual Lotr meta.<br />
<br />
Thanks to everyone who made this past season the most exciting year in my little gaming career and hoping to see many more action and people in the year to come.<br />
<br />
See ya,<br />
<br />
Patrick Malboeuf.<br />
